---
import ServiceLayout from '../../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';

const description = 'Full-stack web development for new products, internal tools, and production applications using Laravel, Astro, Vue, and modern cloud platforms.';
---

<ServiceLayout
  title="Web development"
  description={description}
  serviceType="Full-stack web development"
  slug="web-development"
>
  <h2>Build the useful version first</h2>
  <p>I build web products that solve a concrete problem before they collect infrastructure. That can mean a Laravel application with real business rules, a fast Astro site, an internal dashboard, or a small tool deployed at the edge.</p>
  <p>The goal is not the smallest demo. It is the smallest version you can safely put in front of real people and keep extending.</p>

  <h2>Modernize without breaking production</h2>
  <p>Existing applications need a different kind of speed. I work through framework upgrades, Vue migrations, build tooling, API integrations, and performance problems while preserving the behavior people already depend on.</p>
  <p>Build success is only the start: I test rendered pages, forms, uploads, browser errors, and deployment behavior before calling a migration done.</p>

  <h2>Typical work</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>New Laravel, Astro, or Vue products</li>
    <li>Internal tools and operational dashboards</li>
    <li>Framework and frontend migrations</li>
    <li>Third-party API and payment integrations</li>
    <li>Performance, reliability, and deployment work</li>
  </ul>

  <p>See <a href="/projects/stations">Stations</a> for Laravel on serverless infrastructure, or read how I <a href="/notes/vue-3-migration-is-not-done-when-it-builds">validated a large Vue 3 migration beyond the build step</a>.</p>
</ServiceLayout>
